#: Game.Levels.MeetFin
msgid "# Meet Fin\n"
"\n"
"Welcome to the world of finite types!\n"
"\n"
"In mathematics, finite index sets like В§0 appear\n"
"everywhere вҖ” as indices of vectors, as labels for vertices of a polygon,\n"
"as positions in a sequence. In Lean 4, this finite index set is called\n"
"В§1.\n"
"\n"
"An element of В§2 is not just a number вҖ” it's a number **bundled\n"
"with a proof** that it's less than В§3. This bundling is what makes\n"
"В§4 a proper type rather than just a naming convention. The\n"
"advantage: the type system enforces the bound for you, so out-of-range\n"
"indices are impossible to construct.\n"
"\n"
"В§5 is a *subtype* of В§6 вҖ” the subtype В§7.\n"
"You'll see this subtype pattern again in later courses.\n"
"\n"
"In this world, you'll learn to:\n"
"- **Construct** elements of В§8\n"
"- **Extract** their natural number values\n"
"- **Prove** when two В§9 elements are equal (or not!)\n"
"- **Handle** the edge cases В§10 (empty!) and В§11 (singleton)\n"
"- **Case-split** to reason about all elements of a small В§12 type\n"
"\n"
"Three warnings before we begin:\n"
"1. В§13 starts at **0**, not 1. The elements are В§14.\n"
"   (Why? Because the defining predicate is В§15 on В§16, which\n"
"   naturally gives В§17.)\n"
"2. В§18 is **empty**. There is no natural number less than 0.\n"
"3. Two В§19 elements are equal when their **values** are equal вҖ” you\n"
"   need В§20 to access this fact (you'll also learn the\n"
"   В§21 tactic later in this world).\n"
"\n"
"The boss at the end will ask you to combine all these moves in a single\n"
"proof. Let's begin!"
msgstr ""

