#: Game.Levels.FinTuples
msgid "# Fin Tuples: Functions as Ordered Data\n"
"\n"
"You've learned that В§0 is the finite index set\n"
"В§1, and you can navigate within it using\n"
"В§2, В§3, and В§4. Now comes the payoff:\n"
"\n"
"**A function В§5 is an В§6-tuple.**\n"
"\n"
"This is one of the most useful identifications in formalized\n"
"mathematics. A vector in В§7 is a function\n"
"В§8. A sequence of length 5 is a function\n"
"В§9. The entries of an В§10 matrix are a\n"
"function В§11.\n"
"\n"
"The advantage of using functions instead of lists: the length\n"
"is part of the type. You can't accidentally add a 3-vector to\n"
"a 4-vector вҖ” the types don't match.\n"
"\n"
"In this world, you'll learn to:\n"
"- **Build** tuples using В§12 notation and В§13\n"
"- **Append** elements using В§14\n"
"- **Decompose** from both ends: В§15 (drop first) and В§16 (drop last)\n"
"- **Reconstruct**: В§17 (from front) and В§18 (from back)\n"
"- **Transform** tuples via function composition\n"
"- **Use** tuples as data: verify concrete computations\n"
"- **Prove** two tuples are equal using function extensionality (В§19)\n"
"- **Flip** equations with В§20 for reconstruction proofs\n"
"\n"
"The central tool is **В§21**: two tuples are equal if and only\n"
"if they agree at every index. You already know В§22 for В§23\n"
"elements (two В§24 values are equal when their natural numbers\n"
"are equal). Here, В§25 says two functions are equal when they\n"
"agree on all inputs вҖ” same tactic, new context.\n"
"\n"
"The boss at the end will ask you to prove two differently-described\n"
"tuples are equal, combining reconstruction from both ends with\n"
"extensionality in a single proof."
msgstr ""

